{"questionId":"22642080","questionHtml":"<p>Using the approach started in part (e), or otherwise, find the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;In parts (c) – (f),&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>, for example, represents an ordered&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>-tuple&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p>varies <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi><mo>≠</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> and determines possible values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math> such that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>correctly determines one of the following five cases&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>correctly determines a further two of the following five cases&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>correctly determines the remaining two cases&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>case 1:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&nbs